The Challenge¶

The goal of this kaggle competition is to determine whether a given tweet is about a real disaster or not. This is a very important task, as you would want to respond to real disasters and fake tweets very differently. This is a classic text classification problem.

We can see from the description that for each row in our data there is a location, keyword, and text field that can be used to predict the target outcome (real disaster or not).

Next, we will move on to EDA.

Data Cleaning and Data Preparation¶

Next, we will clean our data and prepare it into the format needed for training. To do this, we will take the following steps:

  1. Break our data into a train and validation set
  2. Tokenize each tweet
  3. Pad the tokenized tweets so that they all have the same length

This will give us everything we need to use this data to train recurrent neural networks

In [ ]:
train, val = train_test_split(full_train_df, test_size=0.2, random_state=4177)

Model Experimentation¶

For this challenge, I want to try out 3 different architectures.

  1. An LSTM model
  2. A GRU model
  3. A simple RNN

My purpose for this challenge is to learn more about building RNNs from scratch. This is why I have chosen these 3 architectures. These 3 architectures are building blocks to understanding the state of the art solutions and how modern RNNs are built. I am sure that I could obtain better results by conducting transfer learning on a state of the art text classification model from tf.hub (like BERT), but that would not help me understand how to build these models from scratch.

Each of these models will have the following architectures

  1. Embedding layer - This will take each tokenized input and create an embedding for each word of length 128
  2. RNN layer - This will be either an LSTM, GRU, or simple RNN. Each will have 128 cells and dropout of 0.25
  3. A Fully Connected Classifier with 2 hidden layers and a sigmoid final activation function
In [ ]:
def make_rnn(rnn_type, num_rnn_layers):
    model = keras.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Embedding(20000,128,input_length=40))
    
    for i in range(num_rnn_layers):
        if rnn_type == 'LSTM':
            model.add(layers.Bidirectional(layers.LSTM(128, dropout=0.25)))
        elif rnn_type == 'GRU':
            model.add(layers.Bidirectional(layers.GRU(128, dropout=0.25)))
        else:
            model.add(layers.Bidirectional(layers.SimpleRNN(128, dropout=0.25)))
        model.add(layers.Dropout(0.25))

    model.add(layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.25))
    model.add(layers.Dense(32, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.25))
    model.add(layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))
    return model

In [ ]:
def plot_training_results(history):
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
    plt.title('Accuracy')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['train', 'validation'], loc='upper left')
    plt.show()

    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.title('Loss')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['train', 'validation'], loc='upper left')
    plt.show()
In [ ]:
plot_training_results(history_lstm)

As you can see, our best validation accuracy was after the first epoch and it was 0.8043. It definitely appears that we overfit our data given that the validation accuracy steadily decreases with each epoch.

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

It is clear from our experiments above that our best model is the LSTM model. This model achieved the best results out of the 3 experiments.

There are many different things that can be tuned to try and improve performance, but given the limited GPU resources that are available to me, I can not conduct a full scale hyperparameter tuning job. Instead, I will experiment with a lower and higher learning rate and see how that changes our results.

In [ ]:
model = make_rnn('LSTM', 1)

epochs = 25

callbacks = [
    keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint("lstm_lower_lr_{epoch}.tf"),
]
model.compile(
    optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001),
    loss="binary_crossentropy",
    metrics=["accuracy"],
)
history_lstm_lower_lr = model.fit(
    x=sequences_train, 
    y=train['target'],
    epochs=epochs,
    callbacks=callbacks,
    validation_data=(sequences_val, val['target']),
    batch_size=16
)

Results and Analysis¶

The following table summarizes the results from our experiments so far.

Model Validation Acc Trainable Params
LSTM 0.8043 2,841,729
GRU 0.7991 2,776,705
Simple RNN 0.7032 2,644,353
LSTM with Lower LR 0.8089 2,841,729
LSTM with Higher LR 0.7971 2,841,729

It is clear that our LSTM with the lower learning rate is our best performing model. We will now take this best performing model and make predictions on the test dataset to submit to kaggle.

Conclusion¶

This competition was a great chance for me to learn about building recurrant neural networks from scratch. While my score is not at the top of the leaderboard, I now have a much better understanding of using Keras to build models from the ground up.

In my experiments, I found that LSTM cells performed the best with GRU close behind. This makes sense given the vast advantages to using LSTM or GRU as opposed to simple RNNs.

There are a handful of improvements that I would love to experiment with given the time. They can be seen below:

  • Experiment with different loss functions and optimizers
  • Experiment with a state of the art text classification model on tf.hub like BERT. In the past, I have used sentence bert models to create embeddings for whole sentences and then used an SVM on those embeddings to classify the sentences. This has yielded very good results for me on other projects and I am curious how that would perform here.
  • Experiment with ensembling the predictions. I could take the LSTM and GRU models and ensemble them to potentially improve the model performance
